Definition of Done
Definition
is a well-understood and clearly documented definition of items that must be established to mark a story (or iteration or project) to be complete
Assessment/Checklist allows work to be defined as “Done.”
Defined by the development team.
Varies per team: Understandable for the team.
Helps to define how many items can be selected for Sprint.
More mature teams: More stringent criteria.
Purpose
Getting a story to a completed state per the definition of done should be the goal of a team and should be used as the basis for planning.


Product Backlog
Definition
the process of creating, maintaining, and prioritizing a dynamic list of all work needed for a project, including new features, bug fixes, enhancements, and technical tasks, to guide the development team's focus and deliver the most value first


Purpose
document the wants and needs for “stuff,” which is prioritized by how much value it is to the business.
Ordering
list of all user requests/requirements
Product Backlog  Grooming
constantly re-evaluated and re-ordered, and items added or removed in a process
Large Items
Are called Epics are broken down into smaller digestible chunks before being considered for work being done.
PBIs
which is any distinct piece of work needed to improve a product, like a new feature, requirement, bug fix, or research task, listed in the Product Backlo



Sprint Backlog
Definition
the prioritized list of tasks, features (user stories), and bugs a development team commits to completing within a single, time-boxed sprint (usually 1-4 weeks) to achieve a specific Sprint Goal
Purpose
is the focused, immediate shopping list for the next two weeks
Source of items
The sprint goal. Work that has needed action from the development team
How are items chosen?
Items are chosen by the level of importance in the upcoming weeks
What does value
orientation vs. results orientation mean?
Value orientation focuses on the why and how the underlying principles, purpose, and consistent action almost like a compass.

Results orientation focuses on the what. Achieving specific, measurable outcomes, acting as the destination that can shift.
Task Board
List of work to be performed during this Sprint. Prioritized with a plan for accomplishment. Is re-evaluated every day during the daily standup.
